\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
The contribution of seed size and number to local adaptation in 
\emph on
Arabidopsis thaliana
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Thomas James Ellis, Froukje Postma, Chris Oakley, Jon Ågren
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Local adaptation can be expressed through several components of fitness,
 some of which may be linked by trade-offs.
 Assessments of the strength of local adaptation and its genetic basis should
 thus include as many components of fitness as possible.
 We quantified local adaptation and examined its genetic basis by mapping
 quantitative trait loci (QTL) for fitness and its components in a population
 of recombinant inbred lines (RILs) derived from a cross between two locally
 adapted populations of Arabidopsis thaliana planted at the sites of the
 two source populations in two years.
 We specifically examined whether number of seeds per fruit is negatively
 correlated with fruit production or seed size, and thus whether the inclusion
 of this fitness component would reduce estimates of local adaptation.
 The local genotype outperformed the non-local genotype in terms of both
 number of fruits and number of seeds per fruit.
 In the RIL population, the two fecundity components were positively correlated,
 and fecundity was positively correlated with survival.
 We found only limited evidence of a trade-off with seed size.
 With a few exceptions, QTL for number of fruits and number of seeds per
 fruit mapped to the same genomic regions, with allelic effects in the same
 direction.
 The results suggest that estimates of the strength of local adaptation
 increase if both fecundity components are considered, and that variation
 in overall vigour rather than trade-offs underlie differences observed
 in individual components of fecundity and fitness.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Local adaptation is the process by which populations evolve in response
 to the specific selection pressures in their native habitat 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "williams1966,kawecki2004conceptual"

\end_inset

.
 A crucial aspect of this process is tuning the investment of resources
 into different life-history stages to match local conditions, such as adult
 growth, offspring number and offspring size 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lack1947significance,stearns1992"

\end_inset

.
 Given that the amount of resources available is finite, there must necessarily
 be trade-offs in the amount of resources which can be allocated to different
 traits, reflected in negative correlations between fitness-related traits
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "stearns1992,roff2002life"

\end_inset

.
 Such trade-offs are a major selective force shaping variation in nature
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hereford2009quantitative"

\end_inset

.
 However, when variation in the ability to acquire resources is large, this
 can lead to positive correlations between traits 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "vannoordwijk1986"

\end_inset

.
 We currently know little about the extent to which local adaptation entails
 tuning allocation to different traits, or an increase in the ability to
 acquire resources.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maximising reproductive output is vital for maximising evolutionary fitness.
 In plants, fecundity is determined by the number of fruits produced, and
 by the number of seeds per fruit 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "silvertown1989paradox"

\end_inset

.
 Seed production is a highly plastic trait that can vary enormously in response
 to variation in resource availability 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "puckridge1967competition,lloyd1987selection,sadras2007evolutionary"

\end_inset

.
 This predicts that selection should act to allow plants to optimally utilise
 the resources available to maximise total seed production.
 Studies of local adaptation in plants typically focus on either fruit productio
n or total seed production as a measure of fecundity (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "latta2009testing,hall2010local,fournier2011map,hancock2011adaptation,agren_genetic_2013"

\end_inset

), yet seed production per fruit has received relatively cursory attention
 (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "agren_reciprocal_2012,hall2006divergent"

\end_inset

).
 It is therefore unclear the extent to which different components of fecundity
 contribute to overall differences in reproductive success, nor whether
 they are negatively or positively correlated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fecundity may also show complex relationships with other fitness-related
 traits.
 Resources allocated to reproduction are not available for investment in
 defence against parasites and predators, or abiotic stressors such as cold
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "stearns1992,roff2002life"

\end_inset

.
 In plants, growth depends on meristems, which can develop into either vegetativ
e or reproductive tissue.
 Since these outcomes are mutually exclusive, there is a necessary trade-off
 between reproduction and further growth 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "geber1990cost"

\end_inset

.
 Providing additional resources to offspring through increased seed size
 may increase the fitness of the offspring 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "smith1974optimal"

\end_inset

, and there is ample evidence of negative correlations between seed mass
 and seed number across species 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "salisbury1942,moles2004seedling,moles2006seed,sera2004number"

\end_inset

.
 However, intraspecific variation in seed mass is dwarfed by variation in
 seed number 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "harper1970"

\end_inset

, and aside from crop species 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gambin2010resource"

\end_inset

, no consistent positive or negative relationship has been found between
 seed size and number within populations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "silvertown1989paradox,venable1992size"

\end_inset

.
 It is therefore unclear whether investment in seed size places a constraint
 on the ability to adpat to local adaptation through increased fecundity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Important insight into the process of local adaptation can be gained by
 examining the genetic architecture of fitness traits 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "merila1999genetic,mauricio2001mapping"

\end_inset

.
 Information about the number and location of quantitative trait loci (QTL)
 with detectable effects on phenotypic variation can reveal the extent to
 which QTL for different components of fitness are found in the same regions
 of the genome, as would be expect if they share a common genetic basis.
 The change in phenotype associated with alleles at these loci can be used
 to infer the genetic mechanisms underlying adpative differentiation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kawecki2004conceptual,savolainen2013ecological,tiffin2014advances"

\end_inset

.
 When there are correlations among components of fitness at the phenotypic
 level, is this reflected in correlated effects of individual QTL on each
 trait, or is this due to the effects of independent loci? Do alleles that
 increase fitness in one environment impose a fitness cost in another environmen
t? Despite extensive evidence that natural populations are locally adapted
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "leimu2008meta,hereford2009quantitative"

\end_inset

, our understanding of the underlying genetic architecture and mechanisms
 remains limited (reviewed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "wadgymar2017identifying"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this study we examine variation in components of fecundity and seed mass
 in 
\emph on
Arabidopsis thaliana, 
\emph default
and investigate the genetic basis of these traits.
 We carried out reciprocal transplant experiments using a large RIL population
 and the parental lines at the source sites in northern Sweden and central
 Italy over two years.
 Previous work has shown that the parental lines are locally adapted, and
 identified survival in Sweden and both survival and fruit production in
 Italy as major determinants of fitness 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "agren_reciprocal_2012"

\end_inset

.
 Here, we quantified the contribution of two components of fecundity, fruit
 number per adult plant and seed number per fruit, as well as survival to
 adaptive differentiation at the two sites.
 We then examine correlations between fecundity, survival and seed mass
 to identify possible trade-offs among adaptive traits.
 Finally, we use the RIL population to identify QTL for seed mass, fruit
 number per plant, seed number per fruit and seed number per plant to test
 the extent to which these traits share a common genetic basis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Materials and methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Data collection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Data on survival, fecundity and fitness are taken from experiments in 2010
 and 2011 described in detail by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "agren_genetic_2013"

\end_inset

.
 Briefly, we set up reciprocal transplant at sites at Rödåsen in central
 Sweden and Castelnuovo di Porto in central Italy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "agren_reciprocal_2012"

\end_inset

.
 At each site, we transplanted seedlings of parental genotypes from both
 sites and 398 recombinant inbred lines (RILs) derived from these parents
 in autumn.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In each following Spring we scored plants for three fitness metrics used
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "agren_genetic_2013"

\end_inset

: (1) survival to reproduction, (2) number of fruits for per plant that
 survived to reproduction (a measure of fecundity), and (3) number of fruits
 per planted seedling (a measure of overall fitness).
 For subsequent analyses we used the mean of trait values across individuals
 of the same genotype.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At each site-year experiment we also collected a single mature but unopened
 fruit, from between 79 and 189 parental plants and between 1917 and 2359
 RIL plants.
 We stored seeds in paper envelopes at room temperature until counting.
 We subsequently counted and weighed all seeds per fruit on a Metler Toledo
 AT261 balance.
 We then calculated mean seed mass as the mass of all seeds in a fruit,
 divided by the total number of seeds.
 We estimated mean values for each line in each site-year experiment as
 the mean across all individuals of the same genotype.
 After excluding lines with fewer than three replicate individuals per line,
 we were able to estimate values for seed number per fruit and seed mass
 for between 340 and 389 RILs for each site-year experiment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also used these data to estimate proxies for total fecundity and total
 fitness.
 We estimated seed number per reproductive plant as the product of fruit
 number per plant and seed number per fruit 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "maddox1983experimental"

\end_inset

.
 Likewise, we estimated seed number per planted seedling as the product
 of fruit number per planted seedling by fruit number per plant.
 Since we did not have data on seed number per fruit for all individuals
 for which data on fruit number was available, we instead multiplied line-mean
 seed number by individual fruit number values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Data manipulations and all subsequent statistical analyses were performed
 in RStudio 0.99.1266 using R 3.3.1 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "r_core_team,rstudio"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fitness differences between parental lines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To assess the relative impact of traits on adaptive differentiation we expressed
 differences in trait means between parental lines as the selective advantage
 of the local genotype.
 We calculated selection coefficients as 
\begin_inset Formula $s=1-w_{A}/w_{B}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{A}$
\end_inset

 is the fitness of the local genotype and 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{B}$
\end_inset

 that of the non-local genotype 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gillespie2010population"

\end_inset

.
 We calculated selection coefficients for overall fitness in terms of both
 fruit number per seedling and seed number per seedling, reflecting fitness
 estimates excluding and including information on seed number.
 We also estimated selection coefficients for two components of fecundity
 (fruit number per reproductive plant and seed number per fruit) and survival.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We estimated confidence intervals around estimates of 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 by parametric bootstrapping.
 We resampled the data for each experiment with replacement 1000 times and
 calculated selection coefficients for each bootstrap sample.
 We estimated 95% confidence intervals for each coefficient as the 25th
 and 975th quantiles of these values.
 We estimate two-tailed 
\emph on
p-
\emph default
values for the null hypothesis that there is no adaptive differentiation
 as the twice the proportion of bootstrap values overlapping zero.
 It is more difficult to determine whether selection coefficients for the
 two measures of overall fitness, fruit number per adult plant and seed
 number per adult plant, differ from one another because these estimates
 are based on common data on fruit number, and as such are not independent.
 Rather than perform a formal test, we instead simply asked whether the
 coefficient for seed number per adult plant was beyond the 95% confidence
 interval for the coefficient for fruit number per adult plant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Correlations between traits
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To assess the strength of trade-offs among traits we calculate Spearman's
 rank correlation coefficient, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, between RIL means for each site-year combination.
 We examined relationships between three pairs of traits: (1) components
 of fecundity (fruit number per reproductive plant and seed number per fruit),
 (2) survival and fecundity (seed number per reproductive plant), and (3)
 fecundity and investment in offspring (seed number per reproductive plant
 and seed mass).
 We performed analyses for data for each site-year experiment separately.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A small number of lines appeared to be outliers that showed consistently
 showed low fecundity, but unusually high seed mass (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:scatter-plots"

\end_inset

).
 To exclude the possibility that these lines could unduly inflate correlation
 coefficients we repeated the analyses for fecundity and offspring investment
 excluding lines with mean seed mass greater than 35mg.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
QTL mapping
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We used the R/qtl package in R to map QTL for four traits: seed mass fruit
 number per reproductive plant, seed number per fruit and seed number per
 reproductive plant 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "broman2009guide,r_core_team"

\end_inset

.
 We performed mapping for RIL mean data for each site-year experiment separately.
 We used Haley–Knott regression using genotype probabilities of the genetic
 markers and pseudomarkers in gaps >2 cM 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "haley1992simple"

\end_inset

.
 We performed a two-QTL scan of the genome with 10,000 permutations of the
 phenotypic data to determine 5% LOD-significance thresholds for inclusion
 of QTL and epistatic interactions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "broman2009guide"

\end_inset

.
 Based on these thresholds, we used R/qtl's automated stepwise model selection
 procedure to identify significant additive QTL and epistatic interactions.
 We first applied a quantile normal transformation to phenotypes before
 model selection.
 Finally we used ANOVA on untransformed data to fit the multiple QTL model
 and calculate effect sizes with respect to the Swedish allele, as well
 as the proportion of the total phenotypic variance explained by each locus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We considered QTL identified for different sites, years or traits to be
 map to the same genomic region if the maximum-likelihood estimate of their
 positions were within 2cM of each other, or if the 95% Bayesian credible
 intervals for these estimates overlapped.
 This approach simplifies interpretation of QTL results, but risks losing
 information about individual genuinely distinct, but nearby QTL.
 This can be justified via the principle of Occam's razor; it is unnecessary
 to posit a a model with two QTL if it does not explain the data any better
 than a model with a single QTL.
 To aid interpretation we also excluded 'poorly-defined' QTL whose credible
 intervals for QTL position were less than 1/4 the length of the shortest
 chromosome (15.2cM; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "agren_genetic_2013"

\end_inset

) from further analysis, because such QTL provide little information about
 position.
\end_layout

