\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This study investigated natural genetic variation for fecundity and its
 components among wild accessions and in a recombinant inbred line population
 of 
\emph on
A.
 thaliana
\emph default
.
 Our results show that seed number per fruit contributes to the fecundity
 advantage of the local geneotypes in both Italy and Sweden.
 We found positive correlations between components of fecundity at both
 sites, and between fecundity and survival to reproduction in both years
 in Italy and in one year in Sweden.
 QTL for seed number per fruit largely overlap with those for fruit number
 per adult plant, suggesting a common genetic basis.
 Local alleles tended to favour the local genotype, with positive effects
 acting through both fecundity components.
 Together, these results indicate that several components of fitness contribute
 to local adaptation in 
\emph on
A.
 thaliana
\emph default
, with little evidence of trade-offs between components.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We found contrasting patterns of the contribution of fecundity to fitness
 at the two sites.
 In Italy, the selective advantage to the local genotype through fruit number
 per plant was approximately twice as large as that through seed number
 per fruit in both years (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:selection"

\end_inset

).
 Nevertheless, selection through seed number per fruit of at least 
\begin_inset Formula $s\geq0.33$
\end_inset

 represents strong selection, and is of similar magnitude to values compiled
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "endler1986"

\end_inset

 for fecundity traits in other systems.
 Furthermore, we are able to detect a significantly greater fitness advantage
 when this is expressed as seed number per seedling than when this is measured
 simply as fruit number per seedling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Sweden, previous work has demonstrated that differences in fecundity
 contribute less to adpative differentiation than do differences in survival
 to reproduction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "agren_reciprocal_2012,agren_genetic_2013"

\end_inset

.
 Consistent with this, we found that selection coefficients for fecundity
 components were substantially weaker in Sweden than in Italy in both year,
 and selection through survival showed significant differentation in 2011
 (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:selection"

\end_inset

).
 In 2010 winter temperatures were especially mild, and native voles destroyed
 a large proportion of the plants at random 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "agren_reciprocal_2012"

\end_inset

.
 As such, selection through survival was very weak in 2010, and seed number
 per fruit was the only fitness component to show significant differentiation
 between the parents.
 By including this fitness components we were also able to detect difference
 in overall fitness which was not detected based on fruit number per plant
 alone (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "agren_reciprocal_2012"

\end_inset

; figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:selection"

\end_inset

).
 This demonstrates that variation in seed number per fruit can be as important
 as variation in survival in maintaining fitness differences in Sweden.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Reproduction requires investment of finite resources, and as such we would
 expect to find trade-offs between fecundity and other fitness traits.
 In fact, we found consistent positive relationships between fecundity component
s at both sites, and between fecundity and survival in Italy and in 2011
 in Sweden (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:scatter-plots"

\end_inset

).
 Lines with the highest fitness show increased fruit number, seed number
 and survival concomitantly.
 This suggests that variation in fecundity between RILs is driven primarily
 by variation in the ability to acquire resources from the environment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "vannoordwijk1986"

\end_inset

.
 This does not mean that trade-offs between fitness components do not exist,
 simply that any trade-offs are overwhelmed by variation in resource acqusition.
 By the same logic, the much stronger correlations observed in Italy than
 in Sweden are evidence that the variation in resource acquisition is much
 greater in Italy than in Sweden, perhaps because of the long period of
 snow cover in Sweden when plants are dormant (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:scatter-plots"

\end_inset

).
 These data demonstrate that local adaptation is driven by parallel evolution
 of correlated traits, but that the importance if these correlations depends
 on local environmental conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several lines of evidence indicate that variation in seed mass places little
 constraint on fecundity.
 Firstly, we found only weak or negligible correlations between fecundity
 and seed mass (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:scatter-plots"

\end_inset

).
 However, this outcome is expected when there is substantial variation in
 resource status 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "venable1992size"

\end_inset

, so the lack of correlation itself is not definitive evidence of a lack
 of constraint.
 Nevertheless, if there were such a correlation, we would expect to see
 QTL with antagonistic effects on seed mass and fecundity regardless of
 resource status.
 In fact we found that only a small number of fecundity QTL colocalised
 with QTL for seed mass, indicating that there is little shared genetic
 basis between these traits (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:QTL-positions"

\end_inset

).
 While these data do not allow us to rule out a trade-off between seed mass
 and fecundity entirely, they do indicate that the importance of seed mass
 in determing variation in adult fitness is dwarfed by variation in resource
 acquisition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
QTL analyses revealed that major-effect loci for fecundity traits largely
 map to the same regions of the genome (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:QTL-positions"

\end_inset

), suggesting a shared genetic basis for these traits.
 One explanation for this is that QTL directly affect variation in resource
 acquisition, and what we observe are their indirect effects on correlated
 traits.
 However, we cannot eliminate the alternative hypothesis that there are
 multiple tightly linked loci with distinct effects on each component of
 fecundity.
 QTL for seed number per plant showed contrasting patterns of association
 with QTL for fecundity components at the two sites.
 In Italy, all QTL for seed number per plant colocalised with QTL for fruit
 number per plant, but only a subset of QTL for seed number per plant.
 In Sweden, we observed the opposite pattern.
 These observations are consistent with the stronger selection observed
 through fruit number per adult plant in Italy and seed number per fruit
 in Sweden (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:selection"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Patterns of allelic effects for fecundity QTL also differed between sites.
 In Italy, the local alleles at almost all QTL for fecundity and its components
 were associated with an increase in fecundity (table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Epistatic-QTL"

\end_inset

 and supporting tables 1-4, figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:QTL-positions"

\end_inset

).
 These effects contribute to the consistent and strong local advantage observed
 for these traits at this site (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:selection"

\end_inset

).
 In Sweden, the additive effects of approximately half of local alleles
 at QTL for the same traits were associated with a decrease in fecundity
 (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:QTL-positions"

\end_inset

), as were the epistatic effects of the local genotype for all four pairs
 of loci with significant interaction effects (table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Epistatic-QTL"

\end_inset

).
 The apparent abundance of maladaptive alleles detected in the RILs is reflected
 in the lack of adaptive differentiation observed between the parents (figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:selection"

\end_inset

).
 Despite this, all local alleles at QTL detected for seed number per fruit
 and per plant in Sweden in 2010 increased fecundity, consistent with the
 significant differentiation through these traits observed in that experiment.
 These observations point to a close concordance between adaptive phenotypic
 differences between the parents and the allelic effects of the underlying
 large-effect QTL.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We found only one instance of antagonistic pleiotropy in allelic effects.
 This was manifested as a trade-off in fruit and seed number per plants
 associated with the QTL at the end of chromosome five.
 This is in contrast to the results of 
