key "oakley2014qtl"

\end_inset

.
 Interestingly, we detected one QTL at the end of chromosome 1 in Sweden
 for which the local allele was associated with increased seed number per
 fruit but decreased fruit number per plant.
 This seems to represent a QTL with .
 Although these traits generally show positive correlations at the phenotypic
 level and a shared genetic basis, this locus seems to show antagonistic
 effects on individual fecundity components.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conclusion, this study has demonstrated that local adaptation in 
\emph on
A.
 thaliana 
\emph default
is driven by changes in multiple components of fitness simultaneously, and
 variation in seed number per fruit makes an important contribution to adaptive
 differentiation.
 Our results imply that variation in resource acquisition rather than resource
 allocation strategy is the main determinant in the differences in fecundity
 and fitness we observe.
 In ongoing work we are investigating adaptation to soil type and resource
 use to begin to elucidate the mechanisms which link resource acquisition
 to adaptive differentiation.
